			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2013</a> paper:</span><br><i>A Model-Driven Approach to Enhance Tool Interoperability Using the Theory of Models of Computation</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/PapaIssaDiallo.html">Papa Issa Diallo</a>, <a href="../profile/JoëlChampeau.html">Joël Champeau</a>, <a href="../profile/LoïcLagadec.html">Loïc Lagadec</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-02654-1_12">10.1007/978-3-319-02654-1_12</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagM">T4B: Horizontal Transformation</span></a><ul><li> The core problem is interoperability across heterogeneous tools, addressed through explicit mappings/exchanges between executable models.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> It leverages formal “models of computation” to reason about and constrain executable model exchanges in a principled way.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> The paper is fundamentally about coordinating and integrating heterogeneous tool chains and execution models.
</li></ul></li></ul>
